'''Mamadou Sarr''' (born 29 August 2005) is a professional [[association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[centre-back]] for {{English football updater|Chelsea}} club [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]]. Born in France, he plays for the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].

==Early life==
Mamadou Sarr<ref>{{cite web |url=https://fdp.fifa.org/assetspublic/ce233/pdf/SquadLists-English.pdf |title=Squad List: FIFA Club World Cup 2025: Chelsea FC (ENG) |publisher=FIFA |page=12 |date=15 June 2025 |access-date=15 June 2025}}</ref> was born on 29 August 2005,<ref name="Lequipe">{{cite news |url=https://www.lequipe.fr/Football/FootballFicheJoueur98838.html |title=Mamadou Sarr |newspaper=L'Équipe |location=Paris |access-date=1 March 2026 |language=fr}}</ref> and is the son of former Senegalese international [[Pape Sarr]]. Mamadou was born in [[Martigues]], Bouches-du-Rhône,<ref name="Lequipe" /> while his father was playing for [[FC Istres|Istres]]. Sarr spent most of his childhood living in [[Nord-Pas-de-Calais]], following his father who spent a large part of his career at [[RC Lens|Lens]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|title=Scouting : Mamadou Sarr, la gloire de son père|url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/scouting-mamadou-sarr-ol-la-gloire-de-son-pere_AV-202205040513.html|access-date=|website=[[RMC Sport]]|date=4 May 2022 |language=fr-FR}}</ref>

==Early career==
Sarr began his football career at Étoile Sportive de [[Saint-Laurent-Blangy]], before joining [[RC Lens|Lens]], where his father plays.<ref name=":0" /> He then moved to [[Olympique Lyonnais Reserves and Academy|Lyon]] in 2018.<ref name=":0" />

During the 2021–22 season, at only 16 years old, he established himself as a starter with ''Les Gones'' under-19 team. He thus played an important role in Lyon's triumph in the [[Coupe Gambardella]] alongside players like [[Hugo Vogel (footballer)|Hugo Vogel]] and [[Mohamed El Arouch]]. He scored in the quarter-final against [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]],<ref>{{Cite web|title=Un bien beau dernier carré |url=https://www.fff.fr/article/6995-un-bien-beau-dernier-carre.html |publisher=French Football Federation|language=fr}}</ref> then in the semi-final against [[ES Troyes AC|Troyes]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Gambardella : l'OL ira au Stade de France ! (3–1) |url=https://www.ol.fr/fr-fr/contenus/articles/2022/04/10/gambardella-compte-rendu-face-a-troyes |publisher=Olympique Lyonnais |language=fr-FR}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web |author=Edward Jay |title=Gambardella: El Arouch, Sarr, Patouillet... Les dernières pépites de l'OL, qui disputent la finale contre Caen |url=https://rmcsport.bfmtv.com/football/gambardella-el-arouch-fuhrer-patouillet-les-dernieres-pepites-de-l-ol-qui-disputent-la-finale-contre-caen_AV-202205070092.html |website=[[RMC Sport]]|date=7 May 2022|language=fr}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|author=Aurélien Macedo |title=Revivez en live commenté la finale de la Coupe Gambardella entre l'OL et Caen ! |url=https://www.footmercato.net/a502706540574200877-suivez-la-rencontre-olympique-lyonnais-u19-caen-u19-en-direct-commente |website=[[Foot Mercato]] |date=7 May 2022|language=fr}}</ref>

==Club career==
===Lyon===
On 27 May 2023, Sarr made his professional debut in Lyon's 3–0 [[2022-23 Ligue 1|Ligue 1]] victory against [[Stade de Reims|Reims]] as a substitute, replacing [[Maxence Caqueret]] in the 83rd minute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ol.fr/en/news/ol-reims-a-spectacular-victory-and-tribute-3-0|title=OL – Reims: A spectacular victory and tribute! (3–0)|publisher=Olympique Lyonnais|date=27 May 2023}}</ref>

On 18 January 2024, Sarr moved on loan to [[R.W.D. Molenbeek (2015)|RWD Molenbeek]] in Belgium until the end of the 2023–24 season,<ref>{{cite web|publisher=RWD Molenbeek|url=https://www.rwdm.be/fr/mamadou-sarr-nouveau-joueur-du-rwdm/|title=MAMADOU SARR NOUVEAU JOUEUR DU RWDM!|work=RWDM |trans-title=MAMADOU SARR IS A NEW RWDM PLAYER!|date=18 January 2024|access-date=18 January 2024|language=fr}}</ref> where he played 10 games, but could not prevent them from being relegated.<ref>{{Cite news |title=Dit is de eindstand in de Relegation Play-offs: RWDM en Eupen zakken|trans-title=This is the final standings in the Relegation Play-offs: RWDM and Eupen are down |url=https://sporza.be/nl/2024/05/11/dit-is-de-eindstand-in-de-relegation-play-offs-rwdm-en-eupen-zakken~1715446770773/|date=2024-05-11 |access-date=2025-06-16 |website=Sporza |language=nl}}</ref>

===Strasbourg===
On 22 August 2024, Sarr joined [[Ligue 1]] fellow [[RC Strasbourg|Strasbourg]] for a transfer fee of €10M and signed a five-year contract with the team.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ol.fr/fr/actualites/transfert-de-mamadou-sarr-au-rc-strasbourg|title=Transfert de Mamadou Sarr au RC Strasbourg|date=21 August 2024|publisher=Olympique Lyonnais|language=fr}}</ref>

===Chelsea===
On 9 June 2025, Sarr moved to [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] on an eight-year contract.<ref>{{Cite web |date=9 June 2025 |title=Chelsea complete Mamadou Sarr signing! |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/chelsea-complete-mamadou-sarr-signing |access-date=2025-06-09 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |language=en}}</ref> On 25 June 2025, he made his Chelsea debut as a late substitute in the 3–0 group stage win over [[Espérance sportive de Tunis|Espérance]] in the [[FIFA Club World Cup|Club World Cup]], a competition that Chelsea would go on to eventually win.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cx2vlrjlkw0t |title= FIFA Club World Cup - Group Stage - Group D: Tunis 0-3 Chelsea |website=BBC Sport |date=25 June 2025 |access-date=25 June 2025}}</ref> However, on 1 August 2025, Chelsea announced that Sarr would be loaned out to [[RC Strasbourg Alsace|Strasbourg]] on a season-long loan.<ref>{{Cite web |date=1 August 2025 |title=Sarr loaned to Strasbourg |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/sarr-loaned-to-strasbourg |access-date=1 August 2025 |publisher=Chelsea F.C.}}</ref>

On 2 February 2026, Sarr was recalled by Chelsea.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mamadou Sarr returns to Chelsea from Strasbourg loan |url=https://www.chelseafc.com/en/news/article/mamadou-sarr-returns-to-chelsea-from-strasbourg-loan |access-date=2 February 2026 |publisher=Chelsea F.C. |date=2 February 2026}}</ref> On 13 February 2026, he made his first ever start for Chelsea in the 4–0 away win against [[Hull City A.F.C.|Hull City]] in the fourth round of the [[2025–26 FA Cup|FA Cup]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/c98g4jxd8jpt |title= FA Cup - 4th Round: Hull City 0-4 Chelsea |website=BBC Sport |date=13 February 2026 |access-date=13 February 2026}}</ref>

==International career==
Eligible to play with Senegal, Sarr chose France for his first selections for the youth team, even recovering the captain's armband on several occasions with [[France national under-17 football team|the under-17s]].<ref name=":0" /> In April 2022, he was selected with the France team for the [[2022 UEFA European Under-17 Championship]] organised in Israel.<ref>{{Cite web|author=Richard Loyant|title=Les vingt joueurs choisis pour l'Euro |url=https://www.fff.fr/article/7346-les-vingt-joueurs-choisis-pour-l-euro.html|publisher=French Football Federation|language=fr}}</ref> He was a starter during the competition, where France was crowned as champions after defeating [[Netherlands national under-17 football team|Netherlands]] 2–1 in the final thanks to [[Saël Kumbedi]]'s brace.<ref>{{Cite web|title=Ils sont champions d'Europe|url=https://www.fff.fr/article/7549-ils-sont-champions-d-europe.html|publisher=French Football Federation|language=fr}}</ref>

In November 2025, Sarr received his first call-up to the [[Senegal national football team|Senegal national team]].<ref>{{Cite web |date=2025-11-06 |title=Senegal: The French federation pulled out all the stops for Mamadou Sarr |url=https://onefootball.com/en/news/senegal-the-french-federation-pulled-out-all-the-stops-for-mamadou-sarr-41928006 |access-date=2025-11-17 |website=OneFootball}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |title=Matchs amicaux Brésil vs Sénégal et Sénégal vs Kenya: le Coach Pape Thiaw publie sa liste |url=https://fsfoot.sn/matchs-amicaux-bresil-vs-senegal-et-senegal-vs-kenya-le-coach-pape-thiaw-publie-sa-liste/ |access-date=2025-11-17 |publisher=Fédération Sénégalaise de Football |language=fr}}</ref> On 19 December 2025, his request to switch international allegiance to Senegal was approved by [[FIFA]].<ref name="FIFA-CAP">{{cite news |url=https://knowledge.fifa.com/change-of-association-platform |title=FIFA Change of Association Platform |website=knowledge.fifa.com |date=19 December 2025|access-date=20 December 2025}}</ref>

For the 2025 edition of the [[2025 Africa Cup of Nations|Africa Cup of Nations]], Sarr was called up by [[Senegal national football team|Senegal]] as part of their 28 men squad. On 18 January 2026, he started and played the full 120 minutes of the final against Morocco as the replacement for the injured and suspended [[Kalidou Koulibaly]] as he helped Senegal to win their 2nd AFCON trophy in the country's history.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/live/cgk8rydnnzkt |title= CAF Africa Cup of Nations - Final: Senegal 1-0 Morocco |website=BBC Sport |date=18 January 2026 |access-date=18 January 2026}}</ref> Overall, Sarr played 3 times for the Senegal national team during this edition of the tournament.{{citation needed|date=March 2026}}

==Style of play==
Trained as a [[centre-back]], Sarr occasionally played as a [[defensive midfielder]] as part of Lyon's youth teams.<ref name=":0" />

